Command console.

These are the available commands you can use in the command console, or with macros enabled. These commands also apply to building command blockers as well.

Any numeric argument to any of these commands can be written as random(low,high) instead of a literal number, and a fresh value between low and high (inclusive) gets rolled each time the command runs. So /spawn bomb random(3,7) 0 1000 2000 bomb5 drops a bomb at a random x between 3 and 7 every time it fires, and /go random(0,100) 0 teleports you to a random horizontal tile within the named range. The token works in every numeric field of every command because the engine's string-to-number routine recognizes it, which also means it works for any numeric field in any hand-authored entity line in main.sif (coordinates, ranges, counts, speeds, healths). The roll is independent on each call, so a switch or macro that fires the same random-bearing command repeatedly gets a new value every time.

/build object, or /bl object: Build an object containing a specified prompt. Typing the object name alone opens the builder form for that object as before. Appending the object's fields after the name skips the form and places the object directly with those fields.

For example: /build platform 0 10 0 10 0 100 marble 0 100 false false places a platform without opening any dialog. The inline form is the authoring verb: it writes the line to the map's main.sif and reloads, so the placement is permanent and survives across map loads. Use /build from a macro or the command console when you want to add content to the map that should stay there; for switch bindings that should only spawn something temporarily, use /spawn instead (described below). The order and type of the fields after the object name match the entity's on-disk line format, so a hand-authored main.sif line and a /build inline argument string are interchangeable.
The object name accepts either the friendly form (the same name the builder menu uses, like moving_platform or security_camera) or the abbreviated on-disk form (like mplatform or camera) — both resolve to the right entity, so you can use whichever you remember. The item-mode form keys (item_door, ranged_item_door, item_passage) resolve to their non-item siblings on disk, and item-mode activates through the lockmode field in the inline args rather than the entity name itself. A malformed inline build silently fails to load that one line on reload while leaving the rest of the map intact.

/changemap mapname x y, or /cm mapname x y: Changes your map to a specified coordinate. On 3d maps the form is /changemap mapname x y z, or /cm mapname x y z, where z is the height to drop you in at.
/charset, or /chr: Brings up the character themes menu. You can also find this in the settings menu of the game.
/delmap, or /dm: Deletes the map you're currently playing.
/draw weapontype weapontype2, or /dr weapontype weapontype2: Equips any weapon with a given type.
/gamestart, or /gs: Freezes the game.
/gamestop, or /gp: Unfreezes the game.
/getall, or /gl: Collects all of the items on the map and gives them to your character.
/give item amount, or /gv item amount: Gives your character an item with a specified amount.
/giveall amount, or /ga amount: Gives your character the specified amount of every item type found across the health, other, and stamina item categories. A negative amount recycles those quantities back out of your inventory instead of adding them, and an amount of zero is a no-op.
/go x y, or /go entity id x y: Moves your character or an npc to a specified coordinate on the map. On 3d maps the form is /go x y z, or /go entity id x y z, where z is the height. This command supports moving the folowing entities. Animals, bosses, helpers, humans, robots, specials, and zombies.
/gozone, or /gz: Gets the list of available zones that you can go to.
/healbones, or /hb: Heals all of your broken bones to being fully functional again.
/help topic, or /hp topic: Brings up a menu containing useful information for a particular topic of interest. Typing this command with no arguments will bring up a menu containing all help topics of interest.
/invclear, or /ic: Clears your entire inventory.
/kill entity id x y, or /kn entity id x y: Kills an npc at a specified coordinate on the map. This command supports killing the folowing entities. Animals, bosses, helpers, humans, robots, specials, and zombies.
/killall, or /kl: Kills all of the npcs on the map. This command supports killing the folowing entities. Animals, bosses, helpers, humans, robots, specials, and zombies.
/macset category category2, or /mc category category2: Changes your current macro pack to a different one. Typing /mc with no arguments will display a menu of all available macro packs.
/mapinfo, or /mi: Opens a read-only dialog with the loaded map's name, owners, description, creation date, modification date (each with how long ago that was), and total size on disk. Works on both decompiled and compiled maps.
/maps, or /mp: Gets the list of available maps that you can visit.
/menu, or /mu: Brings up a menu with several options related to the map you're currently on. You can also build this menu as an alternative to typing the command.
/newmap, or /nm: Creates a new map.
/play sound, or /pl sound: Plays a sound from the misc sounds folder with a given file name. The misc sounds folder is checked in both its decompiled and compiled forms (sounds/decompiled/main/misc and sounds/compiled/main.spack), so a clip served out of either location is playable by name. See the packs help topic for the full explanation of how the two forms interact.
/preffs, or /pf: Brings up the global settings menu. You can also find this in the main menu of the game.
/rawmap, or /rp: Copies the entire data of your map to the clipboard.
/rawdata, or /rd: Pastes the entire data of your map from the clipboard.
/relchar, or /rc: Reloads your current character. This will also clear your inventory, and reset all of your broken bones to being fully functional again.
/relmap true-false, or /rm true-false: Shows a yes/no confirmation dialog before reloading the current map. Pass false instead of true to reload immediately with no prompt — useful from macros or for advanced players who don't want the safety dialog. The argument is required; typing /relmap with no argument speaks a usage hint and does not reload.
/relshields, or /rs: Reloads all shields. This will also unequip the last shield that has been equipped to your character.
/relscripts, or /rt: Reloads all macros.
/relweps, or /rw: Reloads all weapons.
/scriptmode, or /sm: toggles using macros on or off.
/speak text, or /sk text: Speaks any text given by the user.
/spawn object fields, or /sp object fields: The ephemeral cousin of /build. Takes the same arguments — the object name followed by the entity's on-disk fields — and places the entity in the map immediately.

Unlike /build, the spawn is never written to main.sif and the map is never reloaded; the entity exists only in memory and will be gone the next time the map loads. The object name alone (with no fields) speaks an error rather than opening any dialog, since /spawn has no interactive form.
This is the verb to use from a switch's on or off command when you want the switch to summon something temporarily without permanently editing the map. /spawn only works on decompiled maps; once a map is compiled into a .map pack and shipped to players, /spawn silently does nothing on press. Cleanup is the author's responsibility, and today the only cleanup verbs the parser exposes are /killall and /kill, both of which currently affect only npcs — so a /spawn of an npc paired with /killall on a switch's off side cleans up cleanly, but a /spawn of any non-npc entity (platform, door, hazard, item, force field, etc.) has no command available to remove it on flip-off and will persist until the next map reload. Friendly names and on-disk tokens are both accepted, the same way /build accepts them.

/stats, or /st: Brings up the statistics menu. You can also find this in the pause menu of the game.
/suicide, or /sd: Kills your character instantly, depending on how many lives it currently has.

Command blockers can also operate in blacklist and whitelist modes.

Blacklist (false): Only the listed commands are blocked. All other commands remain enabled.
Whitelist (true): Only the listed commands are allowed. All other commands are blocked.
